data.accessibility_caption: Photo by Engineering Facts ðŸ‡ºðŸ‡¸ on February 02, 2026. May be an image of fish and text that says 'EF Engineer ng Facts The UK just dropped a robot fish that eats ocean plastic and powers itself by digesting it'.

caption.text:
Researchers in the United Kingdom have developed a bio-inspired robot fish designed to swim through the ocean and collect microplastics that are difficult to remove using conventional cleanup methods.

The project was developed by scientists at the University of Surrey, where engineers focused on mimicking natural fish movements to reduce energy use and allow smooth navigation through marine environments.

Unlike traditional ocean-cleaning devices, this robot does not rely on batteries or external charging. It uses a synthetic stomach system that breaks down plastic waste and converts it into usable energy.

This approach turns pollution into fuel, meaning the more plastic the robot encounters, the longer it can continue operating autonomously without human intervention.

Innovations like this highlight how robotics and environmental science are merging to address ocean pollution in scalable and sustainable ways, especially as microplastic contamination continues to rise globally.

caption.text:
Cinematic shoegaze fits Francis Doom without stretching the term. The New Jersey project rises from the aftermath of OWEL, anchored by Jay Sakongâ€™s voice and songwriting, drifting between My Bloody Valentineâ€™s density and the emotional reach of Jeff Buckley. His voice has a fluid, elastic quality, able to hold intimacy and intensity in the same breath. Itâ€™s expansive music that still feels intimate, built to overwhelm and confide at the same time.

They played a packed Mercury Lounge last night, and despite the cold gripping the city, the room felt sealed inside Sakongâ€™s world. The songs circle dissolution. Bodies losing definition. Identity thinning out. A desire to be undone by the people and forces closest to you. Thereâ€™s real tenderness threaded through the collapse. Lyrics about flesh caught between teeth sit alongside pleas for connection that land as raw and urgent, never theatrical.

Francis Doom feels poised on the edge of outgrowing rooms like this. Catch them now, while the songs still feel close enough to bruise.

caption.text:
Did you know? ðŸ’§

People who drink bottled water every day can ingest up to 90,000 more microplastic particles each year.

These tiny plastics are invisible to the naked eye, but they end up in your body with every sip.

Over time, they may accumulate and potentially affect your health, including inflammation and hormone disruption.

Even brands labeled as â€œpureâ€ or â€œfilteredâ€ arenâ€™t completely free from microplastics.

Itâ€™s not just waterâ€”plastic packaging, utensils, and food containers all contribute to microplastic exposure.

Switching to alternatives like filtered tap water, glass bottles, or stainless steel containers can help reduce the amount you ingest.

Simple habits like avoiding single-use plastics and choosing sustainable packaging make a big difference over time.

Your daily choices add upâ€”every small step toward reducing plastic can protect your body and the planet.

caption.text:
Australia is racing across the globe, moving north by seven centimeters annually as the worldâ€™s fastest-drifting continent.

Australia is currently the fastest-moving continent on Earth, drifting northward at a remarkable rate of approximately seven centimetersâ€”or about 2.7 inches-every year. This rapid journey is fueled by the relentless movement of tectonic plates deep beneath the planetâ€™s crust. While this shift remains imperceptible to those standing on the ground, it represents a significant geological phenomenon that underscores the constant, dynamic transformation of our world.

This steady migration is more than just a scientific curiosity; it has real-world consequences for global navigation and positioning systems. Because the continentâ€™s coordinates change over time, scientists and cartographers must periodically update global maps to ensure precision for everything from GPS technology to aviation. Australiaâ€™s constant motion serves as a powerful reminder that the Earthâ€™s surface is never truly still, shifting the very foundations of our geography with every passing year.

source: Geoscience Australia. (2020). Australia on the Move. Australian Government.

caption.text:
Researchers at Northeast Forestry University have developed a bamboo-based bioplastic designed to match the strength and heat resistance of conventional petroleum plastics.

The material is made from bamboo cellulose that is chemically structured to maintain durability under high temperatures while still performing like everyday plastic in real-world use.

Unlike traditional plastics that can persist for centuries, this bamboo bioplastic fully breaks down in soil in about 50 days, leaving no toxic residue behind.

The breakthrough could support wider use in packaging, consumer goods, and electronics, showing how plant-based materials may replace fossil-fuel plastics without sacrificing performance.

caption.text:
The Chemistry of Connection: How Cuddling Heals 

The simple act of hugging or cuddling serves as a powerful, non-pharmacological intervention for mental health by triggering a profound neurochemical shift. When we engage in physical touch, the brainâ€™s hypothalamus signals the release of oxytocin, often called the "cuddle hormone," which fosters feelings of trust and safety. Simultaneously, levels of cortisolâ€”the body's primary stress hormoneâ€”drop significantly, actively quieting the nervous system's "fight or flight" response. This hormonal exchange works to alleviate the heavy shadows of depression and soothe the sharp edges of anxiety, providing an immediate sense of emotional grounding. By boosting serotonin and dopamine, regular affectionate touch acts as a natural antidepressant, reinforcing social bonds and reminding the body that it is safe, supported, and not alone.
